@page "/about"

<section class="about-hero">
    <h1>About Ripple</h1>
    <p>
        Ripple is a proof‑of‑concept aquaponics initiative developed as part of an ISU
        honors project. While the system and website model a real nonprofit concept,
        this project is not an active organization. Instead, it explores how 
        sustainable, community‑focused food systems could operate in the Chicagoland area.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="about-section">
    <h2>Project Background</h2>
    <p>
        This project began as an academic exploration into aquaponics — a closed‑loop 
        system that grows fish and plants together. Through research on sustainability, 
        food access, and urban agriculture, the concept of Ripple emerged as a 
        hypothetical model for how such a system could support communities facing food 
        insecurity.
    </p>
    <p>
        Although Ripple is not currently implemented, the project demonstrates how a 
        student‑designed system could integrate research, technology, and community 
        impact into a scalable framework.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="about-section">
    <h2>Conceptual Mission</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Explore how aquaponics can increase access to fresh, nutritious food</li>
        <li>Model partnerships with local food pantries and distribution networks</li>
        <li>Provide a framework for hands‑on learning and community engagement</li>
        <li>Investigate improvements to aquaponics system design</li>
        <li>Demonstrate a scalable concept that other communities could adapt</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="about-section">
    <h2>Why Chicagoland?</h2>
    <p>
        The Chicagoland region provides a compelling case study due to its harsh winters, 
        rising food costs, and limited access to fresh produce in many neighborhoods. 
        This project uses Chicago as a model environment to explore how year‑round 
        aquaponics could help address these challenges.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="about-section">
    <h2>Core Values (Conceptual)</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Community</strong> — Centering people and neighborhoods in system design.</li>
        <li><strong>Sustainability</strong> — Prioritizing resource‑efficient, environmentally conscious methods.</li>
        <li><strong>Education</strong> — Creating opportunities for learning, research, and outreach.</li>
        <li><strong>Equity</strong> — Imagining systems where everyone has access to healthy food.</li>
        <li><strong>Innovation</strong> — Using research to refine and improve aquaponics models.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="about-section">
    <h2>Nonprofit Status (Conceptual)</h2>
    <p>
        Ripple is presented as a hypothetical nonprofit for the purposes of this honors 
        project. While the website references nonprofit structures such as 
        <strong>501(c)(3)</strong> status, these elements are part of the academic 
        demonstration and are not legally established.
    </p>
</section>
